    <p class="text-gray-700">Filet mignon's delicate texture and mild flavor pairs beautifully with elegant Pinot Noir or refined Bordeaux blends that won't overpower the meat. Ribeye's rich marbling and intense beef flavor can handle bold, full-bodied wines like Cabernet Sauvignon, Malbec, or Barolo. The higher fat content in ribeye actually enhances the tannin structure in powerful red wines, creating a more harmonious pairing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine at room temperature with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red wines should be served slightly below room temperature, around 60-65°F (15-18°C), which allows their tannins to integrate smoothly with the steak's proteins and fats. Serving wine too warm (above 68°F) can make it taste overly alcoholic and mask the subtle flavors that complement the beef. Store your wine in a cool place and consider briefly chilling it if your room is particularly warm.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair white wine with steak, and when does it work?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Full-bodied, oak-aged white wines like Chardonnay or white Rhône blends can pair surprisingly well with lighter cuts like filet mignon or when steak is prepared with cream-based sauces. The wine's richness and buttery notes complement the meat without competing, while the acidity cuts through any richness. However, avoid light, crisp whites as they'll be overwhelmed by the steak's intensity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best budget-friendly wine for steak under $20?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for Argentine Malbec, Portuguese Douro reds, or Spanish Monastrell, which offer excellent value with the bold tannins and fruit concentration needed for steak pairings. Côtes du Rhône and Washington State Cabernet Sauvignon also provide restaurant-quality pairings at accessible prices. These wines deliver the structure and intensity to complement beef without breaking the bank.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does the steak's cooking method affect wine pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled steaks develop smoky, charred flavors that pair beautifully with wines aged in American oak or bold, rustic styles like Zinfandel or Australian Shiraz. Pan-seared steaks with butter basting work well with more refined wines like Burgundy or Barolo, while sous-vide preparation preserves the meat's pure flavor, making it ideal for elegant Bordeaux or Napa Cabernet. The cooking method essentially determines whether you want a rustic or refined wine style.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing wine with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is choosing wines that are too light or serving them too cold, which makes the pairing feel unbalanced and leaves the wine tasting thin next to rich, savory beef. Another frequent mistake is ignoring the sauce or seasonings—a peppercorn-crusted steak needs a different wine than one with mushroom sauce. Always consider the complete dish, not just the meat itself.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I decant wine before serving with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young, tannic wines like Cabernet Sauvignon or Barolo benefit from 1-2 hours of decanting to soften harsh tannins and allow flavors to integrate with the steak's richness. Older wines (10+ years) should be decanted just 30 minutes before serving to remove sediment without losing delicate aromatics. Medium-bodied wines like Merlot or Côtes du Rhône typically need only 30-60 minutes to open up perfectly for steak pairings.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good non-alcoholic alternatives that pair well with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium non-alcoholic red wines from producers like Ariel or Fre offer decent tannin structure for steak pairings, though they lack the complexity of traditional wines. For better alternatives, consider rich, dark beverages like aged balsamic drinking vinegar, concentrated grape juice blends, or even strong black tea with herbs, which provide the acidity and depth needed to complement beef's richness. These options won't replicate wine exactly but offer satisfying flavor bridges.</p>
